Problem 1

Data set global_economy contains the annual Exports from many countries. We will analyze data from Argentina.

  1. Plot the Exports series and discuss the main features of the data.

  2. Use an ETS(A,N,N) model to forecast the series, and plot the forecasts.

  3. Compute the RMSE values for the training data.

  4. Compare the results to those from an ETS(A,A,N) model. (Remember that the trended model is using one more parameter than the simpler model.) Discuss the merits of the two forecasting methods for this data set.

  5. Compare the forecasts from both methods. Which do you think is best?

  6. Calculate a 95% prediction interval for the first forecast for each series.

Problem 1 Solutions

  1. Plot the Exports series and discuss the main features of the data.
global_economy |>
  filter(Country == "Argentina") |>
  autoplot(Exports)

There is a huge jump in Exports in 2002, due to the deregulation of the Argentinian peso. Since then, Exports (as a percentage of GDP) has gradually returned to 1990 levels.

  1. Use an ETS(A,N,N) model to forecast the series, and plot the forecasts.
etsANN <- global_economy |>
  filter(Country == "Argentina") |>
  model(ETS(Exports ~ error("A") + trend("N") + season("N")))
etsANN |>
  forecast(h = 10) |>
  autoplot(global_economy)

  1. Compute the RMSE values for the training data.
accuracy(etsANN) |> select(RMSE)
  1. Compare the results to those from an ETS(A,A,N) model. (Remember that the trended model is using one more parameter than the simpler model.) Discuss the merits of the two forecasting methods for this data set.
fit <- global_economy |>
  filter(Country == "Argentina") |>
  model(
    ses = ETS(Exports ~ error("A") + trend("N") + season("N")),
    holt = ETS(Exports ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("N"))
  )
glance(fit)

There is very little difference in training RMSE between these models. So the extra parameter is not doing much.

  1. Compare the forecasts from both methods. Which do you think is best?
fit |>
  forecast(h = 10) |>
  autoplot(global_economy)

  • The forecasts are similar. In this case, the simpler model may be preferred. However, it may also be reasonable to expect an upward trend in these data.
  1. Calculate a 95% prediction interval for the first forecast for each series.
fit |>
  forecast(h = 1) |>
  mutate(PI = hilo(Exports, level = 95))

Problem 2

Find an ETS model for the Gas data from aus_production and forecast the next 5 years. Why is multiplicative seasonality necessary here? Experiment with making the trend damped. Does it improve the forecasts?

Problem 2 Solutions

aus_production |> autoplot(Gas)

  • There is a huge increase in variance as the series increases in level. => That makes it necessary to use multiplicative seasonality.
fit <- aus_production |>
  model(
    hw = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")),
    hwdamped = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("Ad") + season("M")),
  )

fit |>
  forecast(h = "5 years") |>
  autoplot(aus_production, level=NULL)

fit |> glance()
  • The non-damped model seems to be doing slightly better here, probably because the trend is very strong over most of the historical data.

Lets look at the fitted model (without damping).

fit |> tidy()
fit |>
  augment() |>
  filter(.model == "hw") |>
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 24)

Lets look at the residuals.

fit |>
  select(hw) |>
  gg_tsresiduals()

  • There is still some small correlations left in the residuals, showing the model has not fully captured the available information.

  • There also appears to be some heteroskedasticity in the residuals with larger variance in the first half the series.

fit |>
  forecast(h = "5 years") |>
  filter(.model == "hw") |>
  autoplot(aus_production)

While the point forecasts look ok, the intervals are excessively wide.

Alternatively, we can try using an ETS(A,A,A) model after a box-cox transformation.

fit <- aus_production |>
  model(
    hw = ETS(Gas ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")),
    hw.box.cox = ETS(box_cox(Gas,0.4) ~ error("A") + trend("A") + season("A")),
  )

fit |>
  select(hw.box.cox) |>
  gg_tsresiduals()

fit |>
  forecast(h = "5 years") |>
  filter(.model == "hw.box.cox") |>
  autoplot(aus_production)

Problem 3

  1. Apply cross-validation techniques to produce 1 year ahead ETS and seasonal naive forecasts for Portland cement production (from aus_production). Use a stretching data window with initial size of 5 years, and increment the window by one year at a time.

  2. Compute the RMSE of the resulting \(4\)-step-ahead errors. Comment on which forecasts are more accurate. Is this what you expected?

Problem 3 Solutions

  1. Apply cross-validation techniques to produce 1 year ahead ETS and seasonal naive forecasts for Portland cement production (from aus_production). Use a stretching data window with initial size of 5 years, and increment the window by one year at a time.
aus_production |> autoplot(Cement)

fc <- aus_production |>
  model(ets = ETS(Cement ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")),
        snaive = SNAIVE(Cement)) |>
  forecast(h = "4 years")
fc |>
  autoplot(aus_production, level=NULL)

cement_cv <- aus_production |>
  stretch_tsibble(.init = 5*4, .step = 4)

fc <- cement_cv |>
  model(ets = ETS(Cement ~ error("M") + trend("A") + season("M")),
        snaive = SNAIVE(Cement)) |>
  forecast(h = "1 year")
  1. Compute the RMSE of the resulting \(4\)-step-ahead errors. Comment on which forecasts are more accurate. Is this what you expected?
fc |>
  group_by(.id, .model) |>
  mutate(h = row_number()) |>
  ungroup() |>
  as_fable(response = "Cement", distribution = Cement) |>
  accuracy(aus_production, by = c(".model", "h"))
Warning: The future dataset is incomplete, incomplete out-of-sample data will be treated as missing. 
2 observations are missing between 2010 Q3 and 2010 Q4

The ETS results are better for all horizons, although getting closer as \(h\) increases. With a long series like this, I would expect ETS to do better as it should have no trouble estimating the parameters, and it will include trends if required.
